<TITLE> European stocks extend fall as US futures drop </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PARIS, Dec 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European stocks extended losses on Thursday, shedding as much as 2.2 percent along with a fall US futures as a plan by major central banks to boost liquidity failed to reassure investors about the credit squeeze. At 1229 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was down 2 percent at a one-week low of 1,514.38 points. Banking shares sank, with Royal Bank of Scotland down 5.6 percent, HBOS down 7.8 percent and Barclays down 5 percent. "The disappointment after last night's sell-off that's one. Number two, the guys in the US are starting to come into the trading desks and going short and we've got these numbers coming up today and tomrorow, that could be problematic," said Steve Previs of Jefferies International. Other analysts said the decline on the stock market had also been triggered by the fact that interbank lending rates had only fallen very modestly at Thursday's fixing despite the Federal Reserve cut US rates on Tuesday and announced measures on Wednesday to fight the credit cris
